{"title_page": "Fount", "text_new": "{{Wiktionary}}\n'''Fount''' can refer to:\n* The traditional English spelling of the American English [[font]] (i.e. [[typeface]])\n* A [[spring (hydrosphere)|spring]] or [[fountain]], and thus, metaphorically, a source of something beneficial (as in fount of knowledge, wisdom etc.)\n* FOUNT &ndash; a publication for [[Lutheran]] women\n* A fount is also a type of [[plumbing fixture]]\n\n{{disambig}}\n", "text_old": "{{Wiktionary}}\n'''Fount''' can refer to:\n* The traditional English spelling of the American English [[font]] (i.e. [[typeface]]).\n* A [[spring (hydrosphere)|spring]] or [[fountain]], and thus, metaphorically, a source of something beneficial (as in fount of knowledge, wisdom etc.)\n* FOUNT &ndash; a publication for [[Lutheran]] women.\n* A fount is also a type of [[plumbing fixture]].\n\n{{disambig}}\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "don't end lines with a stop in disambiguation pages", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fount"}
{"title_page": "Georgiana Bruce Kirby", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Lead missing|date=March 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{No footnotes|date=March 2020}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=March 2020}}\n{{Tone|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n'''Georgiana Bruce Kirby''' was born on December 7, 1818, in Bristol, England. Her father died three months before her birth while working as a merchant seaman out at sea. Her mother remarried to a man who expended all of the family's savings. Therefore, Bruce only spent two years in formal schooling before leaving her small town to hold various positions in other family's homes. She became a governess at the age of fourteen to an English family who took her to [[Paris]] and then [[Melbourne, Quebec]], where she is known for being a school teacher. She taught her students farming fundamentals, but after a few years, she returned to London in 1837. She got a job working for the American Unitarian minister [[Ezra Stiles Gannett]], who eventually brought her to [[Boston]] at the age of twenty.\n\nAfter a few years of living in Boston, Bruce joined the Transcendentalist community of Brook Farm at [[West Roxbury, Massachusetts]]. Bruce\u2019s brother followed her footsteps and also joined the association in June 1841. The community\u2019s liberal religious beliefs forced all members to live in community, cooperative living. Bruce studied at the school, ran the nursery, and participated in academic discussions about various Brook Farm\u2019s literary members or visitors including Ralph Also Emerson, William Henry Channing, and Margaret Fuller. These authors and the spirit of transcendentalism had a major influence on Bruce\u2019s writing she produced while at Brook Farm. At Brook Farm, she joined the \u201cFancy Group,\u201d which allowed women to use domestic skills to paint lampshades and screens which were sold to raise money to help fund Brook Farm.\n\nBy February 1844, Bruce had supported Brook Farm\u2019s conversion to the French utopian social doctrines of [[Charles Fourier]]; although she felt the community she was once apart of lost its spontaneity; therefore, she moved to New York City. While in New York City, Bruce networked with her friend, Margaret Fuller, and landed a job as [[Eliza Farnham]]'s assistant. Eliza Farnham was most known for being the matron of the Female State Prison in Sing Sing, New York. After working at Sing Sing for a year, Bruce left New York to teach at schools in Illinois and Missouri. However, she returned east to serve as a public school teacher and governess in Pennsylvania and New York.\n\nWith funds she borrowed from [[Horace Greeley]], Bruce traveled to Santa Cruz, California in 1850 where she and Farnham purchased and worked on a farm for two years. Farnham was ridiculed for her radical ideas and decided it was best to travel to the West. They raised poultry and grew potatoes and fruit. While in California, Bruce became very involved in the women\u2019s suffrage movement, the temperance movement, and the anti-slavery crusade.\n\nLater, in 1852, Bruce married Richard Kirby, a local tanner, and had five children. She raised her five children and also continued to write fiction and short stories. She stayed in touch with friends and activists from Brook Farms, and she stayed up to date on women\u2019s rights movements through reform papers such as Greeley\u2019s New York Tribune and National Anti-Slavery Standard. The abolitionist movement and the Civil War fueled Bruce\u2019s belief that women were enslaved, and after the Civil War, she joined the women\u2019s rights movement to secure women\u2019s rights in the Fourteenth and Fifteenth Amendments. By 1869, she raised enough money to fund California\u2019s first local woman suffrage society. And in 1870, she served as vice-president of the San Francisco Women\u2019s Rights Convention. Bruce reported on local lectures by [[Susan B. Anthony]] and [[Elizabeth Cady Stanton]] in the Santa Cruz Sentinel. Bruce also criticized California\u2019s judge decision that prevented women from voting and debated woman suffrage critics. In 1874, at the age of 56, she organized the Santa Cruz Temperance Union, which became affiliated with the WCTU, Women\u2019s Christian Temperance Union, that successfully encouraged the prohibition movement later in the 1920s.\n\nGeorgiana Bruce Kirby died at the age of 68 on January 27, 1887. There is a school named after her in [[Santa Cruz, California]] that supports her ideals. And In 1887, her memoir was published, Years of Experience: An Autobiographical Narrative, in addition to her diary; however, her memoir ends in 1850 when Bruce left New York for California.\n\n==References==\n# {{cite web |last1=Guarneri |first1=Carl |title=Biographical Sketch of Georgiana Bruce Kirby |url=https://documents.alexanderstreet.com/d/1010026827 |website=Alexander Street |accessdate=4 March 2020}}\n# {{cite web |title=Georgiana Bruce Kirby |url=http://newbrookfarm.org/programs/the-women-of-brook-farm/georgiana-bruce-kirby/ |website=New Brook Farm |accessdate=4 March 2020}}\n\n{{ authority control}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kirby, Georgiana Bruce}}\n[[Category:1818 births]]\n[[Category:1887 deaths]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:English schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:American diarists]]\n[[Category:American governesses]]\n[[Category:Women diarists]]\n[[Category:19th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Lead missing|date=March 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{No footnotes|date=March 2020}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=March 2020}}\n{{Tone|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n'''Georgiana Bruce Kirby''' was born on December 7, 1818, in Bristol, England. Her father died three months before her birth while working as a merchant seaman out at sea. Her mother remarried to a man who expended all of the family's savings. Therefore, Bruce only spent two years in formal schooling before leaving her small town to hold various positions in other family's homes. She became a governess at the age of fourteen to an English family who took her to [[Paris]] and then [[Melbourne, Quebec]], where she is known for being a school teacher. She taught her students farming fundamentals, but after a few years, she returned to London in 1837. She got a job working for the American Unitarian minister [[Ezra Stiles Gannett]], who eventually brought her to [[Boston]] at the age of twenty. \n\nAfter a few years of living in Boston, Bruce joined the Transcendentalist community of Brook Farm at [[West Roxbury, Massachusetts]]. Bruce\u2019s brother followed her footsteps and also joined the association in June of 1841. The community\u2019s liberal religious beliefs forced all members to live in community, cooperative living. Bruce studied at the school, ran the nursery, and participated in academic discussions about various Brook Farm\u2019s literary members or visitors including Ralph Also Emerson, William Henry Channing, and Margaret Fuller. These authors and the spirit of transcendentalism had a major influence on Bruce\u2019s writing she produced while at Brook Farm. At Brook Farm, she joined the \u201cFancy Group,\u201d which allowed women to use domestic skills to paint lampshades and screens which were sold to raise money to help fund Brook Farm.  \n\nBy February 1844, Bruce had supported Brook Farm\u2019s conversion to the French utopian social doctrines of [[Charles Fourier]]; although she felt the community she was once apart of lost its spontaneity; therefore, she moved to New York City. While in New York City, Bruce networked with her friend, Margaret Fuller, and landed a job as [[Eliza Farnham]]'s assistant. Eliza Farnham was most known for being the matron of the Female State Prison in Sing Sing, New York. After working at Sing Sing for a year, Bruce left New York to teach at schools in Illinois and Missouri. However, she returned east to serve as a public school teacher and governess in Pennsylvania and New York.   \n\nWith funds she borrowed from [[Horace Greeley]], Bruce traveled to Santa Cruz, California in 1850 where she and Farnham purchased and worked on a farm for two years. Farnham was ridiculed for her radical ideas and decided it was best to travel to the West. They raised poultry and grew potatoes and fruit. While in California, Bruce became very involved in the women\u2019s suffrage movement, the temperance movement, and the anti-slavery crusade.  \n\nLater, in 1852, Bruce married Richard Kirby, a local tanner, and had five children. She raised her five children and also continued to write fiction and short stories. She stayed in touch with friends and activists from Brook Farms, and she stayed up to date on women\u2019s rights movements through reform papers such as Greeley\u2019s New York Tribune and National Anti-Slavery Standard. The abolitionist movement and the Civil War fueled Bruce\u2019s belief that women were enslaved, and after the Civil War, she joined the women\u2019s rights movement to secure women\u2019s rights in the Fourteenth and Fifteenth Amendments. By 1869, she raised enough money to fund California\u2019s first local woman suffrage society. And in 1870, she served as vice-president of the San Francisco Women\u2019s Rights Convention. Bruce reported on local lectures by [[Susan B. Anthony]] and [[Elizabeth Cady Stanton]] in the Santa Cruz Sentinel. Bruce also criticized California\u2019s judge decision that prevented women from voting and debated woman suffrage critics. In 1874, at the age of 56, she organized the Santa Cruz Temperance Union, which became affiliated with the WCTU, Women\u2019s Christian Temperance Union, that successfully encouraged the prohibition movement later in the 1920s.  \n\nGeorgiana Bruce Kirby died at the age of 68 on January 27, 1887. There is a school named after her in [[Santa Cruz, California]] that supports her ideals. And In 1887, her memoir was published, Years of Experience: An Autobiographical Narrative, in addition to her diary; however, her memoir ends in 1850 when Bruce left New York for California.\n\n==References==\n# {{cite web |last1=Guarneri |first1=Carl |title=Biographical Sketch of Georgiana Bruce Kirby |url=https://documents.alexanderstreet.com/d/1010026827 |website=Alexander Street |accessdate=4 March 2020}}\n# {{cite web |title=Georgiana Bruce Kirby |url=http://newbrookfarm.org/programs/the-women-of-brook-farm/georgiana-bruce-kirby/ |website=New Brook Farm |accessdate=4 March 2020}}\n\n{{ authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kirby, Georgiana Bruce}}\n[[Category:1818 births]]\n[[Category:1887 deaths]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:English schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:American diarists]]\n[[Category:American governesses]]\n[[Category:Women diarists]]\n[[Category:19th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgiana_Bruce_Kirby"}
{"title_page": "Esma\u00ebl Gon\u00e7alves", "text_new": "====St Mirren (loan)====\nOn 22 January 2013, Gon\u00e7alves signed on loan with [[Scottish Premier League]] club [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] until the end of the 2012\u201313 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren sign Portuguese striker Esmael Goncalves from Rio Ave|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21153890|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 January 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126024053/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21153890|archive-date=26 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The day after signing, he was quoted in the local newspaper ''[[Paisley Daily Express]]'' that he could be \"the next Drogba\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Goncalves vows to be St Mirren's answer to Drogba |url=http://www.paisleydailyexpress.co.uk/renfrewshire-sport/renfrewshire-football/renfrewshire-football-st-mirren/2013/01/24/goncalves-vows-to-be-st-mirren-s-answer-to-drogba-87085-32665593/ |publisher=Paisley Daily Express |date=24 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007183423/http://www.paisleydailyexpress.co.uk/renfrewshire-sport/renfrewshire-football/renfrewshire-football-st-mirren/2013/01/24/goncalves-vows-to-be-st-mirren-s-answer-to-drogba-87085-32665593/ |archivedate=7 October 2013 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> \n\nGon\u00e7alves scored his first goal for the club on his debut in the [[2012\u201313 Scottish League Cup|Scottish League Cup]] semi-final in a 3\u20132 win over [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] at [[Hampden Park]],<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 3 \u2013 2 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21106906|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 January 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017213946/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21106906|archive-date=17 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> with his being the club's first goal against the [[Glasgow]] side since March 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 3 Celtic 2: Hoops' hopes of treble over after Buddies set up Hearts final|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2269113/St-Mirren-3-Celtic-2.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=28 January 2013|access-date=17 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202081308/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2269113/St-Mirren-3-Celtic-2.html|archive-date=2 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Three days later, he made his first [[Scottish Premier League]] appearance against [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]], [[Nutmeg (football)|nutmegging]] the goalkeeper in a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 2 \u2013 1 Inverness CT|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21156141|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 January 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814114315/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21156141|archive-date=14 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In his first [[Scottish Cup]] appearance against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]], Gon\u00e7alves scored both goals of a 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 2\u20130 St Johnstone|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21209383|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414122506/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21209383|archive-date=14 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored another goal against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] at [[St Mirren Park]] in a 2\u20131 loss in the sixth round of the [[Scottish Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 1 \u2013 2 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21556779|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 March 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414122735/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21556779|archive-date=14 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2013, Gon\u00e7alves played in the [[2012\u201313 Scottish League Cup|Scottish League Cup final]] against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] where he scored the equalising goal and provided an assist for [[Conor Newton]]'s third in a 3\u20132 victory Buddies' first [[2012\u201313 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] and their first major trophy since 1987.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 3 \u2013 2 Hearts|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21732267|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 March 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151231161131/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21732267|archive-date=31 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly after scoring, he lifted his jersey, which had the inscription ''\"Forca F\u00e1bio Faria\"'' (\"Come on [[F\u00e1bio Faria]]\"), dedicating a goal to a player whose career ended after a heart condition. Gon\u00e7alves was then booked by the referee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Esmael dedicated goal to F\u00e1bio Faria|trans-title=Esmael dedicou golo a F\u00e1bio Faria|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/Internacional/Portugueses/interior.aspx?content_id=810545|publisher=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=Portuguese|date=18 March 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515051750/http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/Internacional/Portugueses/interior.aspx?content_id=810545|archive-date=15 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1\u20131 draw against Celtic on 31 March, Gon\u00e7alves caused controversy when he dived to win the penalty after being fouled by [[Emilio Izaguirre]], with television pictures proving that there was no contact.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 1 \u2013 1 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21915425|publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 March 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821195921/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21915425|archive-date=21 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> After the match, he was given a two-match ban by the SFA, following an issue of complaint for his action of diving,<ref>{{cite news|title=SFA cites St Mirren's Esmael Goncalves for simulation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22008827|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405033526/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22008827|archive-date=5 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> which he accepted.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren's Esmael Goncalves accepts two-match ban|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22033900|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407225803/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22033900|archive-date=7 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> He told BBC Scotland that he would be happy to make a return to St. Mirren in the future.<ref>{{cite news|title=Esmael Goncalves happy to return to St Mirren|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22297851|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130428051208/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22297851|archive-date=28 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The club was willing to make his transfer permanent, but Rio Ave announced that this would not be the case, and said that such a deal would cost \u00a3400,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer Talk, June 11: Great expectations and the latest moves|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-transfer-news/transfer-talk-june-11-2013-1945635|publisher=Daily Record|date=11 June 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210152525/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-transfer-news/transfer-talk-june-11-2013-1945635|archive-date=10 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====APOEL (loan)====\nOn 3 July 2013, Gon\u00e7alves completed a season-long loan move to Cypriot side [[APOEL F.C.|APOEL]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=9834&tt=graphic&lang=l1|title=Esma\u00ebl Gon\u00e7alves|publisher=APOEL FC|language=Greek|date=3 July 2013|accessdate=3 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204191001/http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=9834&tt=graphic&lang=l1|archivedate=4 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe scored on his debut against [[NK Maribor]] at [[GSP Stadium]] on 31 July, opening the scoring in a 1\u20131 first leg draw for the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League#Qualifying rounds|third qualifying round]] of the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2014/matches/round=2000477/match=2011713/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Battling Maribor hold APOEL|trans-title=|publisher=UEFA|date=31 July 2013|accessdate=31 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803013523/http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2014/matches/round=2000477/match=2011713/postmatch/report/index.html|archive-date=3 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 October, he scored the \n\n===Asia===\n[[File:Isma first goal for Esteghlal 2.0.jpg|thumb|Moment of Isma first goal for Esteghlal against [[Paykan F.C.|Paykan]]]]\nGon\u00e7alves signed for Uzbek club [[Pakhtakor Tashkent FK|Pakhtakor Tashkent]] in January 2018.<ref name = \"uzbek\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42857103 |title=Isma Goncalves and Hearts benefit from sale to Pakhtakor Tashkent - Craig Levein |work= |publisher=BBC |date=29 January 2018 |accessdate=29 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201044640/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42857103 |archive-date=1 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 January 2019, Gon\u00e7alves moved to [[Esteghlal F.C.|Esteghlal]] on an 18-month-long contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fcesteghlal.ir/news/item/3540/\u0628\u0627+\u0627\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645+\u0641\u062a\u062d\u06cc\u060c+\u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc\u0644+\u06af\u0648\u0646\u06a9\u0627\u0644\u0648\u0633+\u0628\u0647+\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644+\u067e\u06cc\u0648\u0633\u062a|title=\u0628\u0627 \u0627\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u062a\u062d\u06cc\u060c \u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc\u0644 \u06af\u0648\u0646\u06a9\u0627\u0644\u0648\u0633 \u0628\u0647 \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u067e\u06cc\u0648\u0633\u062a|trans-title=With Fathi's announcement, Esma\u00ebl Gon\u00e7alves joined Esteghlal|publisher=Esteghlal F.C.|date=26 January 2019|accessdate=26 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129170910/http://fcesteghlal.ir/news/item/3540/%D8%A8%D8%A7+%D8%A7%D8%B9%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85+%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AD%DB%8C%D8%8C+%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B9%DB%8C%D9%84+%DA%AF%D9%88%D9%86%DA%A9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%88%D8%B3+%D8%A8%D9%87+%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%84+%D9%BE%DB%8C%D9%88%D8%B3%D8%AA|archive-date=29 January 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was given the squad shirt number 20.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tarafdari.com/node/1216403|title=\u0634\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0647\u0646 \u0627\u06cc\u0633\u0645\u0627\u060c \u0646\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0641\u06a9\u0646 \u0648 \u067e\u0627\u062a\u0648\u0633\u06cc \u0628\u0627\u0632\u06cc\u06a9\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u062c\u062f\u06cc\u062f \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u0645\u0634\u062e\u0635 \u0634\u062f|trans-title=The shirt numbers of Isma, Noorafkan and Patosi were revealed|date=7 February 2019|access-date=6 February 2019|publisher=Tarafdari|language=Persian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209180105/https://www.tarafdari.com/node/1216403|archive-date=9 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He made his\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bissau-Guinean footballer}}\n{{Portuguese name|Tavares Cruz|Silva Gon\u00e7alves}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Esma\u00ebl Gon\u00e7alves\n| image = Esma\u00ebl Gon\u00e7alves Esteghlal-Esteghlal Khuzestan 20190501.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = Isma with [[Esteghlal F.C.|Esteghlal]] in 2019\n| fullname = Esma\u00ebl Ruti Tavares Cruz <br /> da Silva Gon\u00e7alves<ref name=\"esma\u00ebl_profile\">{{cite news |title=Esma\u00ebl Portuguese Football Federation Profile |url=https://www.fpf.pt/portal/page/portal/PORTAL_FUTEBOL/PESQUISA/DETALHE?amb=fpf&agente=642603&tipoagente=J |work=[[Portuguese Football Federation]] |date= |accessdate=29 November 2011 |language=Portuguese }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> {{Dead link|date=January 2019}}\n| height = {{convert|1.85|m|abbr=on}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1991|6|25|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Bissau]], Guinea-Bissau\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]] / [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132008\n| youthclubs1 = [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]]\n| youthyears2 = 2008\u20132011\n| youthclubs2 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| years1 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs1 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| caps1 = 18\n| goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2012\u20132015\n| clubs2 = [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]]\n| caps2 = 18\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2013\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 12\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[APOEL F.C.|APOEL]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 10\n| goals4 = 3\n| years5 = 2014\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Veria F.C.|Veria]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 15\n| goals5 = 2\n| years6 = 2015\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Anorthosis Famagusta]] (loan)\n| caps6 = 15\n| goals6 = 9\n| years7 = 2015\n| clubs7 = [[Ettifaq FC|Al-Ettifaq]]\n| caps7 = 0\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs8 = [[Anorthosis Famagusta]]\n| caps8 = 33\n| goals8 = 9\n| years9 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs9 = [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]]\n| caps9 = 35\n| goals9 = 13\n| years10 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs10 = [[Pakhtakor Tashkent FK|Pakhtakor Tashkent]]\n| caps10 = 21\n| goals10 = 12\n| years11 = 2019\n| clubs11 = [[Esteghlal F.C.|Esteghlal]]\n| caps11 = 13\n| goals11 = 3\n| years12 = 2019-\n| clubs12 = [[Matsumoto Yamaga FC|Matsumoto Yamaga]]\n| caps12 = 3\n| goals12 = 0\n<!-- This is for LEAGUE GOALS ONLY. Do NOT include other goals. -->| nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132008\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam2 = [[Guinea-Bissau national football team|Guinea-Bissau]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| pcupdate = 29 November 2019\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n\n'''Esma\u00ebl Ruti Tavares Cruz da Silva Gon\u00e7alves''' (born 25 June 1991), also known as '''Isma''', is a Bissau-Guinean professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for Japanese club [[Matsumoto Yamaga FC]] and [[Guinea-Bissau national football team|Guinea-Bissau national team]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Nice===\nGon\u00e7alves was born in [[Bissau]], the capital city of [[Guinea-Bissau]], but moved to [[Portugal]] with his family at the age of three.<ref name=\"esma\u00ebl_career\">{{cite news |title=Esma\u00ebl Gon\u00e7alves: guia de Djal\u00f3 espera FC Porto |url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/franca/esmael-goncalves-nice-yannick-djalo-franca-ligue-1-fc-porto/1287571-1487.html |work=Mais Futebol |date=9 October 2011 |accessdate=29 November 2011 |language=Portuguese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124141/https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/franca/esmael-goncalves-nice-yannick-djalo-franca-ligue-1-fc-porto/1287571-1487.html |archive-date=9 February 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He began his football career with [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]]. Gon\u00e7alves spent three years at the club before venturing to France to sign with [[OGC Nice|Nice]] after being invited for a trial at the club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Qui est Esmael Gon\u00e7alves? |url=http://www.actufoot06.com/article.php?id=5698 |work=Actufoot |date=21 November 2008 |accessdate=29 November 2011 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518224514/http://www.actufoot06.com/article.php?id=5698 |archive-date=18 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Prior to signing with the club, he drew interest from English club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref name=\"esma\u00ebl_career\"/> Gon\u00e7alves spent two years in Nice's youth academy before earning promotion to the club's reserve team in the [[Championnat de France amateur 2]] for the [[2010\u201311 in French football|2010\u201311 season]]. Following a successful half season at reserve level, he was called up to the senior team in January 2011 and made his professional debut in a 2\u20130 defeat to [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]], appearing as a substitute.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bordeaux v. Nice Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/53860 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=20 January 2011 |accessdate=29 November 2011 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524125551/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/53860 |archive-date=24 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> That was his only senior team appearance of the campaign.\n\nOn 30 June 2011, Gon\u00e7alves signed his first professional contract, agreeing to a three-year deal until 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nice \u2013 Contrats pro pour Goncalves et V\u00e9ron\u00e8se |url=http://fr.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1465650.html |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |date=30 June 2011 |accessdate=29 November 2011 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406170417/http://fr.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1465650.html |archive-date=6 April 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was officially promoted to the senior team by manager [[\u00c9ric Roy]] and assigned the number 24 shirt for the [[2011\u201312 in French football|2011\u201312 season]]. He scored twice that season, including the winner in a 4\u20133 victory at [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] on the last day, 20 May 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=A story of endings |url=https://www.ogcnice.com/en/news/33854/a-story-of-endings- |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=OGC Nice |date=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Rio Ave===\nOn 3 August 2012, Nice confirmed on its official website that Gon\u00e7alves would be returning to Portugal to join first division club [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]]. Gon\u00e7alves had previously expressed his desire to join the [[Vila do Conde]]-based club in order to be near his family.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gon\u00e7alv\u00e8s (Nice) rejoint Rio Ave |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Goncalves-rejoint-rio-ave/303386 |work=[[L'Equipe]] |date=3 August 2012 |accessdate=20 August 2012 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124553/https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Goncalves-rejoint-rio-ave/303386 |archive-date=9 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====St Mirren (loan)====\nOn 22 January 2013, Gon\u00e7alves signed on loan with [[Scottish Premier League]] club [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] until the end of the 2012\u201313 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren sign Portuguese striker Esmael Goncalves from Rio Ave|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21153890|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 January 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126024053/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21153890|archive-date=26 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The day after signing, he was quoted in the local newspaper ''[[Paisley Daily Express]]'' that he could be \"the next Drogba\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Goncalves vows to be St Mirren's answer to Drogba |url=http://www.paisleydailyexpress.co.uk/renfrewshire-sport/renfrewshire-football/renfrewshire-football-st-mirren/2013/01/24/goncalves-vows-to-be-st-mirren-s-answer-to-drogba-87085-32665593/ |publisher=Paisley Daily Express |date=24 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007183423/http://www.paisleydailyexpress.co.uk/renfrewshire-sport/renfrewshire-football/renfrewshire-football-st-mirren/2013/01/24/goncalves-vows-to-be-st-mirren-s-answer-to-drogba-87085-32665593/ |archivedate=7 October 2013 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> \n\nGon\u00e7alves scored his first goal for the club on his debut in the [[2012\u201313 Scottish League Cup|Scottish League Cup]] semi-final in a 3\u20132 win over [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] at [[Hampden Park]],<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 3 \u2013 2 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21106906|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 January 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017213946/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21106906|archive-date=17 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> with his being the club's first goal against the [[Glasgow]] side since March 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 3 Celtic 2: Hoops' hopes of treble over after Buddies set up Hearts final|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2269113/St-Mirren-3-Celtic-2.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=28 January 2013|access-date=17 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202081308/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2269113/St-Mirren-3-Celtic-2.html|archive-date=2 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Three days later, he made his first [[Scottish Premier League]] appearance against [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]], [[Nutmeg (football)|nutmegging]] the goalkeeper in a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 2 \u2013 1 Inverness CT|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21156141|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 January 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814114315/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21156141|archive-date=14 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In his first [[Scottish Cup]] appearance against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]], Gon\u00e7alves scored both goals of a 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 2\u20130 St Johnstone|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21209383|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414122506/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21209383|archive-date=14 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored another goal against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] at [[St Mirren Park]] in a 2\u20131 loss in the sixth round of the [[Scottish Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 1 \u2013 2 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21556779|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 March 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414122735/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21556779|archive-date=14 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2013, Gon\u00e7alves played in the [[2012\u201313 Scottish League Cup|Scottish League Cup final]] against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] where he scored the equalising goal and provided an assist for [[Conor Newton]]'s third in a 3\u20132 victory Buddies' first [[2012\u201313 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] and their first major trophy since 1987.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 3 \u2013 2 Hearts|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21732267|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 March 2013|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151231161131/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21732267|archive-date=31 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly after scoring, he lifted his jersey, which had the inscription ''\"Forca F\u00e1bio Faria\"'' (\"Come on [[F\u00e1bio Faria]]\"), dedicating a goal to a player whose career ended after a heart condition. Gon\u00e7alves was then booked by the referee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Esmael dedicated goal to F\u00e1bio Faria|trans-title=Esmael dedicou golo a F\u00e1bio Faria|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/Internacional/Portugueses/interior.aspx?content_id=810545|publisher=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=Portuguese|date=18 March 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515051750/http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/Internacional/Portugueses/interior.aspx?content_id=810545|archive-date=15 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1\u20131 draw against Celtic on 31 March, Gon\u00e7alves caused controversy when he dived to win the penalty after being fouled by [[Emilio Izaguirre]], with television pictures proving that there was no contact.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 1 \u2013 1 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21915425|publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 March 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821195921/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21915425|archive-date=21 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> After the match, he was given a two-match ban by the SFA, following an issue of complaint for his action of diving,<ref>{{cite news|title=SFA cites St Mirren's Esmael Goncalves for simulation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22008827|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405033526/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22008827|archive-date=5 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> which he accepted.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren's Esmael Goncalves accepts two-match ban|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22033900|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407225803/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22033900|archive-date=7 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> He told BBC Scotland that he would be happy to make a return to St. Mirren in the future.<ref>{{cite news|title=Esmael Goncalves happy to return to St Mirren|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22297851|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130428051208/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22297851|archive-date=28 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The club was willing to make his transfer permanent, but Rio Ave announced that this would not be the case, and said that such a deal would cost \u00a3400,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer Talk, June 11: Great expectations and the latest moves|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-transfer-news/transfer-talk-june-11-2013-1945635|publisher=Daily Record|date=11 June 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210152525/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-transfer-news/transfer-talk-june-11-2013-1945635|archive-date=10 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====APOEL (loan)====\nOn 3 July 2013, Gon\u00e7alves completed a season-long loan move to Cypriot side [[APOEL F.C.|APOEL]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=9834&tt=graphic&lang=l1|title=Esma\u00ebl Gon\u00e7alves|publisher=APOEL FC|language=Greek|date=3 July 2013|accessdate=3 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204191001/http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=9834&tt=graphic&lang=l1|archivedate=4 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe scored on his debut against [[NK Maribor]] at [[GSP Stadium]] on 31 July, opening the scoring in a 1\u20131 first leg draw for the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League#Qualifying rounds|third qualifying round]] of the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2014/matches/round=2000477/match=2011713/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Battling Maribor hold APOEL|trans-title=|publisher=UEFA|date=31 July 2013|accessdate=31 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803013523/http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2014/matches/round=2000477/match=2011713/postmatch/report/index.html|archive-date=3 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 October, he scored the equaliser against [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] in APOEL's 2\u20131 defeat at [[Stade Chaban-Delmas]] for the third matchday of the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League group stage|group stage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2014/matches/round=2000469/match=2012534/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Henrique swoops as Bordeaux snatch late win|trans-title=|publisher=UEFA|date=24 October 2013|accessdate=24 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115220745/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2014/matches/round=2000469/match=2012534/postmatch/report/index.html|archive-date=15 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first [[Cypriot First Division|league]] goals in APOEL's 5\u20130 home victory against [[AEK Kouklia F.C.|AEK Kouklia]] on 2 December, in a match which Gon\u00e7alves managed to score a hat-trick.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/12/02/cyprus/1-division/apoel-nicosia/ae-kouklion/1513383/|title=APOEL vs. AE Kouklion 5\u20130|trans-title=|publisher=Soccerway|date=2 December 2013|accessdate=2 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210161049/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/12/02/cyprus/1-division/apoel-nicosia/ae-kouklion/1513383/|archive-date=10 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 31 December, APOEL terminated his contract by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=10607&tt=graphic&lang=l1|script-title=el:\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03af\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7|trans-title=Announcement|publisher=APOEL FC|language=Greek|date=31 December 2013|accessdate=31 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101065515/http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=10607&tt=graphic&lang=l1|archive-date=1 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2014, [[Veria F.C.|Veria]] signed Gon\u00e7alves on a one-year loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veriafc.gr/index.php/2012-10-10-16-25-23/543-podosfairistis-tis-veroias-o-ismael-goncalves|title=\u03a0\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u0395\u03a1\u039f\u0399\u0391\u03a3 \u03bf \u0399SMAEL GONCALVES|trans-title=ISMAEL GONCALVES player of VERIA|publisher=VERIA FC|language=Greek|date=14 January 2014|accessdate=14 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116123904/http://www.veriafc.gr/index.php/2012-10-10-16-25-23/543-podosfairistis-tis-veroias-o-ismael-goncalves|archive-date=16 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He scored his first [[Superleague Greece|Superleague]] goal in a defeat to [[P.A.O.K. F.C.|PAOK]].\n\n===Heart of Midlothian===\nAfter a stint in Cyprus with [[Anorthosis Famagusta FC|Anorthosis]], Gon\u00e7alves signed for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] in January 2017.<ref name = \"greek\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38799666 |title=Hearts sign Esmael Goncalves, Alexandros Tziolis and Anastasios Avlonitis |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=30 January 2017 |accessdate=30 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024171217/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38799666 |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Hearts paid a transfer fee of about \u00a3170,000 for his services and he made his debut in a 4\u20131 win over Rangers on 1 February. Gon\u00e7alves scored 15 goals in 42 appearances for Hearts, until he was sold to [[Pakhtakor Tashkent FK|Pakhtakor Tashkent]] for \u00a3350,000 in January 2018.<ref name = \"uzbek\"/>\n\n===Asia===\n[[File:Isma first goal for Esteghlal 2.0.jpg|thumb|Moment of Isma first goal for Esteghlal against [[Paykan F.C.|Paykan]]]]\nGon\u00e7alves signed for Uzbek club [[Pakhtakor Tashkent FK|Pakhtakor Tashkent]] in January 2018.<ref name = \"uzbek\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42857103 |title=Isma Goncalves and Hearts benefit from sale to Pakhtakor Tashkent - Craig Levein |work= |publisher=BBC |date=29 January 2018 |accessdate=29 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201044640/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42857103 |archive-date=1 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 January 2019, Gon\u00e7alves moved to [[Esteghlal F.C.|Esteghlal]] on an 18-month-long contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fcesteghlal.ir/news/item/3540/\u0628\u0627+\u0627\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645+\u0641\u062a\u062d\u06cc\u060c+\u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc\u0644+\u06af\u0648\u0646\u06a9\u0627\u0644\u0648\u0633+\u0628\u0647+\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644+\u067e\u06cc\u0648\u0633\u062a|title=\u0628\u0627 \u0627\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u062a\u062d\u06cc\u060c \u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc\u0644 \u06af\u0648\u0646\u06a9\u0627\u0644\u0648\u0633 \u0628\u0647 \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u067e\u06cc\u0648\u0633\u062a|trans-title=With Fathi's announcement, Esma\u00ebl Gon\u00e7alves joined Esteghlal|publisher=Esteghlal F.C.|date=26 January 2019|accessdate=26 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129170910/http://fcesteghlal.ir/news/item/3540/%D8%A8%D8%A7+%D8%A7%D8%B9%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85+%D9%81%D8%AA%D8%AD%DB%8C%D8%8C+%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B9%DB%8C%D9%84+%DA%AF%D9%88%D9%86%DA%A9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%88%D8%B3+%D8%A8%D9%87+%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%82%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%84+%D9%BE%DB%8C%D9%88%D8%B3%D8%AA|archive-date=29 January 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was given the squad shirt number 20.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tarafdari.com/node/1216403|title=\u0634\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0647\u0646 \u0627\u06cc\u0633\u0645\u0627\u060c \u0646\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0641\u06a9\u0646 \u0648 \u067e\u0627\u062a\u0648\u0633\u06cc \u0628\u0627\u0632\u06cc\u06a9\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u062c\u062f\u06cc\u062f \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u0645\u0634\u062e\u0635 \u0634\u062f|trans-title=The shirt numbers of Isma, Noorafkan and Patosi were revealed|date=7 February 2019|access-date=6 February 2019|publisher=Tarafdari|language=Persian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209180105/https://www.tarafdari.com/node/1216403|archive-date=9 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on 7 February, in a 4\u20130 win against [[Paykan F.C.|Paykan]], coming on as an 81st-minute substitute for [[Morteza Tabrizi]]. He scored his first goal for Esteghlal in the same game just two minutes after coming on as a substitute.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.varzesh3.com/news/1589947/\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0634-\u0628\u0627\u0632\u06cc-\u067e\u06cc\u06a9\u0627\u0646-\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644-\u062a\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646-\u0644\u06cc\u06af-\u0628\u0631\u062a\u0631-18-11-139705-12-96|title=\u067e\u06cc\u06a9\u0627\u0646 0 - \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644 4\u061b \u0622\u0645\u0627\u062f\u0647 \u0628\u0627\u0634 \u062a\u06cc\u0645 \u067e\u0631\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0628\u0647 \u0644\u06cc\u06af|trans-title= Paykan 0 - Esteghlal 4|date=7 February 2019|accessdate=7 February 2019|publisher=Varzesh3}}</ref> On 1 June, Esteghlal announced Isma's contract was terminated by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcesteghlal.ir/news/item/3940/\u0627\u06cc\u0633\u0645\u0627+\u0627\u0632+\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644+\u062c\u062f\u0627+\u0634\u062f|title=\u0627\u06cc\u0633\u0645\u0627 \u0627\u0632 \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u062c\u062f\u0627 \u0634\u062f|trans-title=Isma left Esteghlal.|publisher=Esteghlal F.C.|date=1 June 2019|accessdate=1 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601220132/http://www.fcesteghlal.ir/news/item/3940/%25D8%25A7%25DB%258C%25D8%25B3%25D9%2585%25D8%25A7%2B%25D8%25A7%25D8%25B2%2B%25D8%25A7%25D8%25B3%25D8%25AA%25D9%2582%25D9%2584%25D8%25A7%25D9%2584%2B%25D8%25AC%25D8%25AF%25D8%25A7%2B%25D8%25B4%25D8%25AF|archive-date=1 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGon\u00e7alves signed for Japanese club [[Matsumoto Yamaga FC|Matsumoto Yamaga]] in September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yamaga-fc.com/archives/183714|title=\u30a4\u30ba\u30de\u9078\u624b\u52a0\u5165\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b|trans-title=Notice of joined Isma|publisher=Matsumoto Yamaga FC|date=9 September 2019|accessdate=9 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929130706/https://www.yamaga-fc.com/archives/183714|archive-date=29 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 November, he made his debut for the Japanese side as a substitute in a 1\u20130 defeat against [[Yokohama F. Marinos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yamaga-fc.com/archives/189761|title=2019 \u660e\u6cbb\u5b89\u7530\u751f\u547d J1\u30ea\u30fc\u30b0\u7b2c32\u7bc0 vs \u6a2a\u6d5c\uff26\u30fb\u30de\u30ea\u30ce\u30b9\u6226\u306e\u7d50\u679c|publisher=Yamaga FC|date=23 November 2019|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== International career ==\nThough born in Guinea-Bissau, Gon\u00e7alves is a [[naturalised citizen]] of Portugal. He has represented them at [[Portugal national under-17 football team|under-17 level]].<ref name=\"esma\u00ebl_career\"/> In 2010, he was called up to the [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal under-20 team]] to participate in training sessions as the team was preparing for the [[2011 FIFA U-20 World Cup]]. Gon\u00e7alves, however, showed up to the camp out of shape and was, ultimately, not considered for the tournament by coach [[Il\u00eddio Vale]].<ref name=\"esma\u00ebl_career\"/>\n\nHe earned one cap for [[Guinea-Bissau national football team|Guinea-Bissau]] on 22 March 2018, starting in a 2\u20130 friendly loss to [[Burkina Faso national football team|Burkina Faso]] in [[Limeil-Br\u00e9vannes]], France.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guin\u00e9e-Bissau / Esma\u00ebl Gon\u00e7alves : \u00ab \u00c0 la hauteur \u00bb |url=https://www.football365.fr/guinee-bissau-esmael-goncalves-a-hauteur-7414345.html |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=Football 365 |date=23 March 2018 |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 29 November 2019}}<ref name=\"sw\">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/esmael-ruti-tavares-cruz-da-silva-goncalves/252235/|title=ESMA\u00cbL GON\u00c7ALVES - Career statistics - Soccerway|access-date=26 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126225310/https://int.soccerway.com/players/esmael-ruti-tavares-cruz-da-silva-goncalves/252235/|archive-date=26 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Ligue 1|2010\u201311]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ligue 1]]\n|1||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Ligue 1|2011\u201312]]\n|17||2||2||1||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||19||3\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!18!!2!!2!!1!!0!!0!!colspan=2|\u2014!!colspan=2|\u2014!!20!!3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]]\n|[[2012\u201313 Primeira Liga|2012\u201313]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Primeira Liga]]\n|6||0||1||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||8||0\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Primeira Liga|2013\u201314]]\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Primeira Liga|2014\u201315]]\n|12||1||2||1||3||1||4<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\">Appearances in the [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]</ref>||1||0||0||21||4\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!18!!1!!3!!1!!4!!1!!4!!1!!0!!0!!29!!4\n|-\n|[[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] (loan)\n|[[2012\u201313 Scottish Premier League|2012\u201313]]\n|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|12||3||2||3||2||2