K players]]\n[[Category:Esteghlal F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Matsumoto Yamaga FC players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Cypriot First Division players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:Prince Mohammad bin Salman League players]]\n[[Category:Persian Gulf Pro League players]]\n[[Category:J1 League players]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Bissau-Guinean expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Bissau-Guinean expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Bissau-Guinean expatriate sportspeople in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Bissau-Guinean expatriate sportspeople in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Bissau-Guinean expatriate sportspeople in Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Bissau-Guinean expatriate sportspeople in Iran]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Iran]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Iran]]\n[[Category:Bissau-Guinean expatriate sportspeople in Japan]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "151.235.179.200", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esma%C3%ABl_Gon%C3%A7alves"}
{"title_page": "Frederick Thomas Sargood", "text_new": "{{for|Sargood's father, also a businessman and politician|Frederick James Sargood}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Sir Frederick Sargood\n| honorific-suffix =  [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]]\n| image = Frederick Thomas Sargood.jpg\n| title = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| term_start = 29 March 1901\n| term_end = 2 January 1903\n| successor = [[Robert Reid (Australian politician, born 1842)|Robert Reid]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1834|5|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Walworth]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1903|1|2|1834|5|30}} \n| death_place = [[Taihape]], [[New Zealand]]\n| nationality = [[English Australian]]\n| spouse = Marian Australia Rolfe\n| party = [[Free Trade Party]]\n| relations = [[Frederick James Sargood|F. J. Sargood]] ''(father)''\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Clerk, soldier\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Sir Frederick Thomas Sargood''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG}} (30 May 1834 \u2013 2 January 1903) was an [[Australia]]n politician, Minister of Defence and Education in the [[Government of Victoria]] 1890\u20131892 and Senator in the [[Australian Senate]] 1901\u201303.\n\n==Early life==\nSargood was born in [[Walworth]], [[London]], the eldest child of [[Frederick James Sargood]] (later a member of the old [[Victorian Legislative Council]]), and Emma, daughter of Thomas Rippon, [[Chief Cashier]] of the [[Bank of England]].<ref name=adb>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography\n|last=Rickard\n|first=John\n|authorlink= \n|year=1976\n|volume=6\n|pp=87\u201388\n|id=A060099b\n|title=Sargood, Sir Frederick Thomas (1834 - 1903) \n|accessdate=2009-12-15}}</ref> F. T. Sargood was educated at private schools and arrived with his family aboard the ''Clifton'' in [[Melbourne]] on 12 February 1850.<ref name=adb/> He initially worked as a clerk in the Public Works Department, but in 1851 joined his father's softgoods business,Sargood, King & Co., and in 1859 became a junior partner in it. In the same year he joined the Victorian volunteer artillery as a [[private (rank)|private]] and eventually reached the rank of [[lieutenant-colonel]]. He also took an interest in rifle shooting. In 1858 Sargood married Marian Australia, daughter of George Rolfe, later a politician.<ref name=adb/>\n\n==Political career==\nIn May 1874 Sargood entered the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] by winning a by-election for [[Central Province (Victoria)|Central Province]],<ref name=parl/> and in 1875 he became the first chairman of the [[Melbourne Harbour Trust]]. Sargood was a commissioner of savings banks in 1874\u201380.<ref name=adb/> Sargood's wife Marian died in childbirth on 6 January 1880, he resigned from the council and visited England later the same year with his nine children.<ref name=adb/> Sargood was appointed a delegate by the Victorian government to represent the colony before the Imperial Commission for the protection of British possessions abroad. Sargood married Julia Tomlin on 2 December 1880 on the [[Isle of Wight]]<ref name=adb/> and returned to Melbourne in 1882.\n\nSargood held the Legislative Council Province of [[South Yarra Province|South Yarra]] from November 1882 to March 1901.<ref name=parl>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=710\n|title=Sargood, Sir Frederick Thomas\n|publisher=Parliament of Victoria\n|accessdate=8 November 2012\n}}</ref> In March 1883 Sargood became an Honorary Minister in the [[James Service]] government. In the same year when the Defence Department was formed, he was the first Minister of Defence, and carried through the reorganization of the defences which involved the changeover from volunteer to militia forces. Rifle clubs were formed and the important cadet corps movement for schoolboys was also due to Sargood's efforts. In 1885 he took the additional portfolio of Minister of Water-supply, and held both positions until the resignation of the ministry in February 1886. He was appointed Vice-President of the Melbourne Centennial Exhibition of 1888 and subsequently Executive Vice-President and Treasurer. Sargood was also president of the [[Melbourne Chamber of Commerce]] 1886\u20131888, and his name stood very high in the business world. When he joined his father's business it was a comparatively small one, but now under the name of Sargood Butler and Nichol it had become one of the largest in Australia, with branches in other cities. It was subsequently extended to [[New Zealand]] and before Sargood's death the number of employees was over 5000. When [[William Hearn (legal academic)|William Hearn]] died in 1888, Sargood became Leader of the Legislative Council, in which position he examined all bills coming from the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]] and showed much critical ability. He joined the [[James Munro (Australian politician)|James Munro]] ministry in November 1890 as Minister of Defence and of Education, but withdrew when the ministry was reconstructed under [[William Shiels]] in February 1892, because he was unable to agree with Shiels's adhesion to the \"one man one vote\" principle.\n\nAlthough Sargood' political leanings were conservative, he had piloted the first Factories Act through the Council with skill, and in his own firm, the Saturday half-holiday had been brought in as far back as 1852. Sargood joined the [[George Turner (Australian politician)|George Turner]] government in September 1894 as Minister of Defence, but about three months later again resigned on a question of principle. He again took up the position of Leader of the Council and had a prominent part in the [[Federation of Australia|Federation movement]]. His views on the tariff prevented his being elected as one of the Victorian delegates to the 1897 convention, but at the [[1901 Australian general election|first federal election]] in 1901 he was elected as one of the [[Australian Senate|senators]] for Victoria in spite of the opposition of the protectionist press. When the Senate met he was nominated for the position of [[President of the Australian Senate|President]] which, however, went to [[Richard Chaffey Baker|Sir Richard Baker]] by 21 votes to 12. Sargood, however, took a leading position in the Senate.\n\n==Late life and legacy==\n[[File:(1)Gore_Hill_Cemetery-4.jpg|thumb|Sargood family vault in Gore Hill cemetery, Sydney]]\n[[File:RipponGrange.JPG|thumb|''Rippon Grange'', the mansion built for son Frederick George Sargood]]\nSargood was created Companion of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (CMG) in 1885 and was knighted KCMG in 1890. He died suddenly while on a holiday in [[Taihape]], [[New Zealand]] on 2 January 1903.<ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=ODT19030119.2.105 ''Otago Daily Times'', 19 January 1903]. Retrieved 6 June 2016</ref> He was the first serving Australian Senator to die in office. Lady Sargood survived him with five sons and four daughters of the first marriage, and one daughter of the second.\n\nSargood was prominently connected with many philanthropic and religious movements. {{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n\nThe large [[Rippon Lea Estate]] in [[Elsternwick]] was originally built for Sargood in 1868.\n\nOne son, Frederick George Sargood, moved to Sydney and became a prominent retailer. He lived for a time in ''Rippon Grange'', a mansion in Water Street, [[Wahroonga, New South Wales|Wahroonga]], which was designed by [[Howard Joseland]].<ref>[https://federation-house.wikispaces.com/Rippon+Grange,+Wahroonga Federation house wikispaces]</ref> The Sargood family vault is located in [[Gore Hill cemetery]], [[St Leonards, New South Wales|St Leonards]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{Dictionary of Australian Biography|First=Frederick Thomas|Last=Sargood|shortlink=0-dict-biogSa-Sp.html#sargood1}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sargood, Frederick Thomas}}\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:Australian federationists]]\n[[Category:People from Southwark]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to colonial Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Australian politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for Victoria]]\n[[Category:Free Trade Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|Sargood's father, also a businessman and politician|Frederick James Sargood}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Sir Frederick Sargood\n| honorific-suffix =  [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]]\n| image = Frederick Thomas Sargood.jpg\n| title = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| term_start = 29 March 1901\n| term_end = 2 January 1903\n| successor = [[Robert Reid (Australian politician)|Robert Reid]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1834|5|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Walworth]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1903|1|2|1834|5|30}} \n| death_place = [[Taihape]], [[New Zealand]]\n| nationality = [[English Australian]]\n| spouse = Marian Australia Rolfe\n| party = [[Free Trade Party]]\n| relations = [[Frederick James Sargood|F. J. Sargood]] ''(father)''\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Clerk, soldier\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Sir Frederick Thomas Sargood''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG}} (30 May 1834 \u2013 2 January 1903) was an [[Australia]]n politician, Minister of Defence and Education in the [[Government of Victoria]] 1890\u20131892 and Senator in the [[Australian Senate]] 1901\u201303.\n\n==Early life==\nSargood was born in [[Walworth]], [[London]], the eldest child of [[Frederick James Sargood]] (later a member of the old [[Victorian Legislative Council]]), and Emma, daughter of Thomas Rippon, [[Chief Cashier]] of the [[Bank of England]].<ref name=adb>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography\n|last=Rickard\n|first=John\n|authorlink= \n|year=1976\n|volume=6\n|pp=87\u201388\n|id=A060099b\n|title=Sargood, Sir Frederick Thomas (1834 - 1903) \n|accessdate=2009-12-15}}</ref> F. T. Sargood was educated at private schools and arrived with his family aboard the ''Clifton'' in [[Melbourne]] on 12 February 1850.<ref name=adb/> He initially worked as a clerk in the Public Works Department, but in 1851 joined his father's softgoods business,Sargood, King & Co., and in 1859 became a junior partner in it. In the same year he joined the Victorian volunteer artillery as a [[private (rank)|private]] and eventually reached the rank of [[lieutenant-colonel]]. He also took an interest in rifle shooting. In 1858 Sargood married Marian Australia, daughter of George Rolfe, later a politician.<ref name=adb/>\n\n==Political career==\nIn May 1874 Sargood entered the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] by winning a by-election for [[Central Province (Victoria)|Central Province]],<ref name=parl/> and in 1875 he became the first chairman of the [[Melbourne Harbour Trust]]. Sargood was a commissioner of savings banks in 1874\u201380.<ref name=adb/> Sargood's wife Marian died in childbirth on 6 January 1880, he resigned from the council and visited England later the same year with his nine children.<ref name=adb/> Sargood was appointed a delegate by the Victorian government to represent the colony before the Imperial Commission for the protection of British possessions abroad. Sargood married Julia Tomlin on 2 December 1880 on the [[Isle of Wight]]<ref name=adb/> and returned to Melbourne in 1882.\n\nSargood held the Legislative Council Province of [[South Yarra Province|South Yarra]] from November 1882 to March 1901.<ref name=parl>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=710\n|title=Sargood, Sir Frederick Thomas\n|publisher=Parliament of Victoria\n|accessdate=8 November 2012\n}}</ref> In March 1883 Sargood became an Honorary Minister in the [[James Service]] government. In the same year when the Defence Department was formed, he was the first Minister of Defence, and carried through the reorganization of the defences which involved the changeover from volunteer to militia forces. Rifle clubs were formed and the important cadet corps movement for schoolboys was also due to Sargood's efforts. In 1885 he took the additional portfolio of Minister of Water-supply, and held both positions until the resignation of the ministry in February 1886. He was appointed Vice-President of the Melbourne Centennial Exhibition of 1888 and subsequently Executive Vice-President and Treasurer. Sargood was also president of the [[Melbourne Chamber of Commerce]] 1886\u20131888, and his name stood very high in the business world. When he joined his father's business it was a comparatively small one, but now under the name of Sargood Butler and Nichol it had become one of the largest in Australia, with branches in other cities. It was subsequently extended to [[New Zealand]] and before Sargood's death the number of employees was over 5000. When [[William Hearn (legal academic)|William Hearn]] died in 1888, Sargood became Leader of the Legislative Council, in which position he examined all bills coming from the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]] and showed much critical ability. He joined the [[James Munro (Australian politician)|James Munro]] ministry in November 1890 as Minister of Defence and of Education, but withdrew when the ministry was reconstructed under [[William Shiels]] in February 1892, because he was unable to agree with Shiels's adhesion to the \"one man one vote\" principle.\n\nAlthough Sargood' political leanings were conservative, he had piloted the first Factories Act through the Council with skill, and in his own firm, the Saturday half-holiday had been brought in as far back as 1852. Sargood joined the [[George Turner (Australian politician)|George Turner]] government in September 1894 as Minister of Defence, but about three months later again resigned on a question of principle. He again took up the position of Leader of the Council and had a prominent part in the [[Federation of Australia|Federation movement]]. His views on the tariff prevented his being elected as one of the Victorian delegates to the 1897 convention, but at the [[1901 Australian general election|first federal election]] in 1901 he was elected as one of the [[Australian Senate|senators]] for Victoria in spite of the opposition of the protectionist press. When the Senate met he was nominated for the position of [[President of the Australian Senate|President]] which, however, went to [[Richard Chaffey Baker|Sir Richard Baker]] by 21 votes to 12. Sargood, however, took a leading position in the Senate.\n\n==Late life and legacy==\n[[File:(1)Gore_Hill_Cemetery-4.jpg|thumb|Sargood family vault in Gore Hill cemetery, Sydney]]\n[[File:RipponGrange.JPG|thumb|''Rippon Grange'', the mansion built for son Frederick George Sargood]]\nSargood was created Companion of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (CMG) in 1885 and was knighted KCMG in 1890. He died suddenly while on a holiday in [[Taihape]], [[New Zealand]] on 2 January 1903.<ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=ODT19030119.2.105 ''Otago Daily Times'', 19 January 1903]. Retrieved 6 June 2016</ref> He was the first serving Australian Senator to die in office. Lady Sargood survived him with five sons and four daughters of the first marriage, and one daughter of the second.\n\nSargood was prominently connected with many philanthropic and religious movements. {{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n\nThe large [[Rippon Lea Estate]] in [[Elsternwick]] was originally built for Sargood in 1868.\n\nOne son, Frederick George Sargood, moved to Sydney and became a prominent retailer. He lived for a time in ''Rippon Grange'', a mansion in Water Street, [[Wahroonga, New South Wales|Wahroonga]], which was designed by [[Howard Joseland]].<ref>[https://federation-house.wikispaces.com/Rippon+Grange,+Wahroonga Federation house wikispaces]</ref> The Sargood family vault is located in [[Gore Hill cemetery]], [[St Leonards, New South Wales|St Leonards]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{Dictionary of Australian Biography|First=Frederick Thomas|Last=Sargood|shortlink=0-dict-biogSa-Sp.html#sargood1}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sargood, Frederick Thomas}}\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:Australian federationists]]\n[[Category:People from Southwark]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to colonial Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Australian politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for Victoria]]\n[[Category:Free Trade Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Robert Reid (Australian politician)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederick_Thomas_Sargood"}
{"title_page": "Collins Street Baptist Church", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name                 = Collins Street Baptist Church\n| fullname             =\n| image                = Collins Street Baptist Church Melbourne.jpg\n| imagesize            =\n| landscape            =\n| caption              = \n| location             = 174 Collins Street, Melbourne\n| country              = Australia\n| coordinates          =\n| denomination         = Baptist\n| tradition            =\n| membership           =\n| attendance           =\n| website              = [http://www.csbc.org.au/ csbc.org.au]\n| former name          =\n| bull date            =\n| founded date         = 1845\n| founder              =\n| dedication           =\n| dedicated date       = \n| consecrated date     =\n| cult                 =\n| relics               = \n| events               =\n| past bishop          =\n| people               =\n| status               =\n| functional status    =\n| heritage designation =\n| designated date      =\n| architect            =\n| architectural type   = Greek Revival architecture\n| style                =\n| groundbreaking       =\n| completed date       =\n| construction cost    =\n| closed date          =\n| demolished date      =\n| parish               =\n| deanery              =\n| archdeaconry         =\n| diocese              = \n| province             =\n| presbytery           =\n| synod                =\n| circuit              =\n| district             =\n| division             = \n| subdivision          =\n| archbishop           = \n| bishop               = \n| dean                 =\n| subdean              =\n| provost              =\n| provost-rector       =\n| viceprovost          =\n| canon                =\n| canonpastor          =\n| precentor            =\n| archdeacon           =\n| prebendary           =\n| rector               =\n| vicar                =\n| curate               =\n| priest               = \n| pastor               = \n| asstpriest           =\n| minister             =\n| assistant            =\n| honpriest            =\n| deacon               = \n| deaconness           =\n| seniorpastor         =\n| abbot                =\n| chaplain             =\n| reader               =\n| organistdom          =\n| director             =\n| organist             =\n| organscholar         =\n| chapterclerk         =\n| laychapter           =\n| warden               =\n| flowerguild          =\n| musicgroup           =\n| parishadmin          =\n| serversguild         =\n| logo                 =\n| logosize             =\n}}\n'''Collins Street Baptist Church''' is a [[Baptist]] church in central [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. Founded on this site in 1845, it is the oldest Baptist church in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. It is known as the former church of the outspoken minister [[Tim Costello]], brother of the former [[Treasurer of Australia]], [[Peter Costello]].\n\n==History==\nThe first Baptist service in Melbourne was held in 1838 in a tent on a vacant allotment of land opposite the present church. The first chapel was built on the current site in 1845. In the late 1850s it was decided to enlarge the building. The current church was designed [[Joseph Reed (architect)|Joseph Reed]], the architect who designed the [[Melbourne Town Hall]] and several other prominent Melbourne churches, and the new church was opened in 1862. Unlike most Melbourne churches of the period, which are either [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] or [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]], Collins St Baptist is in the form of a classical temple, with four [[Corinthian columns]] facing the street. According to the church's website, this \"reflects the Baptist understanding of the church as a gathered community of believers rather than as a special building.\"\n\n==Building==\nIn conformity with the Baptist dislike of decoration in churches, the interior has plain plastered walls. It has arched moulded windows, a double aisle and side seats facing the [[pulpit]]. A central raised pulpit emphasises the stress in Baptist theology on the Word of God being read and preached as central features of the services of worship. Seating is arranged in a \"U\" shape around the central axis determined by the pulpit and the Communion table. There is no form of decoration other than some detail in the windows and carving on the pulpit and Communion furniture. No cross or symbol appears in the church.\n\nBaptist tradition also disapproved of music in churches, but in 1854 a small organ was installed. In 1885 the a larger organ was installed. This was restored and expanded in 1974.\n\nJim Barr was appointed a minister of Collins Street Baptist Church in 1991, when he established the Urban Mission Unit (now known as Urban Seed), recruited the first group of mission interns and implemented the SEEDS training program. This time was followed by his appointment as the Pastor at Collins Street Baptist Church from 1994 to 2000. During this time Jim was responsible for the pastoral and liturgical leadership of the Church community as well as taking a keen interest in the world around the Collins Street church.\n\n==People==\n[[Tim Costello]], a lawyer, republican activist and former [[St Kilda, Victoria|Mayor of St Kilda]] as well as a Baptist minister, was appointed the minister of the Collins Street Baptist Church and director of the Urban Mission Unit in 1995, the year before his brother, [[Peter Costello]], became the federal treasurer. Tim Costello's outspoken comments on many social and political issues brought new attention to the church. Under his leadership, the Urban Mission Unit rose to prominence as a leading voice on urban, business, social and political issues including homelessness, drug addiction, [[problem gambling]] and poverty.  The Urban Mission Unit changed its name to Urban Seed in 2001.  Costello left the position in 2004 on being appointed chief executive officer of [[World Vision]] Australia. The senior minister is now the Revd Simon Holt.\n\nSeveral historically notable people have been members of the church. During the early 20th century numerous women active in the Victorian women's movement were members, including [[Cecilia Downing]], [[Margaret McLean]] and [[Bessie Rees]].<ref>Smart, J. Downing, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A140031b.htm Cecilia (1858 - 1952)], Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 14, Melbourne University Press, 1996, pp 28-30.</ref><ref>Hyslop, A. McLean, Margaret (1845 - 1923), ''[http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A100322b.htm Australian Dictionary of Biography]'', Volume 10, Melbourne University Press, 1986, p. 331.</ref><ref>Smart, J, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/AS10409b.htm?hilite=Collins%3BStreet%3Bbaptist Rees, Elizabeth Laurie (Bessie) (1865 - 1939)], Australian Dictionary of Biography, Supplementary Volume, Melbourne University Press, 2005, pp 335-336.</ref> The politicians [[Denis Lovegrove]] and [[Robert Reid (Australian politician, born 1842)|Robert Reid]] were members as were the prominent Melbourne Syme family, including the owner of ''The Age'', [[David Syme]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.csbc.org.au/ Collins Street Baptist Church]\n*[http://www.urbanseed.org/ Urban Seed]\n{{coord|-37.8148|144.9677|type:landmark_region:AU|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Baptist churches in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1862]]\n[[Category:19th-century Baptist churches]]\n[[Category:Heritage-listed buildings in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:1845 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Collins Street, Melbourne]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name                 = Collins Street Baptist Church\n| fullname             =\n| image                = Collins Street Baptist Church Melbourne.jpg\n| imagesize            =\n| landscape            =\n| caption              = \n| location             = 174 Collins Street, Melbourne\n| country              = Australia\n| coordinates          =\n| denomination         = Baptist\n| tradition            =\n| membership           =\n| attendance           =\n| website              = [http://www.csbc.org.au/ csbc.org.au]\n| former name          =\n| bull date            =\n| founded date         = 1845\n| founder              =\n| dedication           =\n| dedicated date       = \n| consecrated date     =\n| cult                 =\n| relics               = \n| events               =\n| past bishop          =\n| people               =\n| status               =\n| functional status    =\n| heritage designation =\n| designated date      =\n| architect            =\n| architectural type   = Greek Revival architecture\n| style                =\n| groundbreaking       =\n| completed date       =\n| construction cost    =\n| closed date          =\n| demolished date      =\n| parish               =\n| deanery              =\n| archdeaconry         =\n| diocese              = \n| province             =\n| presbytery           =\n| synod                =\n| circuit              =\n| district             =\n| division             = \n| subdivision          =\n| archbishop           = \n| bishop               = \n| dean                 =\n| subdean              =\n| provost              =\n| provost-rector       =\n| viceprovost          =\n| canon                =\n| canonpastor          =\n| precentor            =\n| archdeacon           =\n| prebendary           =\n| rector               =\n| vicar                =\n| curate               =\n| priest               = \n| pastor               = \n| asstpriest           =\n| minister             =\n| assistant            =\n| honpriest            =\n| deacon               = \n| deaconness           =\n| seniorpastor         =\n| abbot                =\n| chaplain             =\n| reader               =\n| organistdom          =\n| director             =\n| organist             =\n| organscholar         =\n| chapterclerk         =\n| laychapter           =\n| warden               =\n| flowerguild          =\n| musicgroup           =\n| parishadmin          =\n| serversguild         =\n| logo                 =\n| logosize             =\n}}\n'''Collins Street Baptist Church''' is a [[Baptist]] church in central [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. Founded on this site in 1845, it is the oldest Baptist church in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. It is known as the former church of the outspoken minister [[Tim Costello]], brother of the former [[Treasurer of Australia]], [[Peter Costello]].\n\n==History==\nThe first Baptist service in Melbourne was held in 1838 in a tent on a vacant allotment of land opposite the present church. The first chapel was built on the current site in 1845. In the late 1850s it was decided to enlarge the building. The current church was designed [[Joseph Reed (architect)|Joseph Reed]], the architect who designed the [[Melbourne Town Hall]] and several other prominent Melbourne churches, and the new church was opened in 1862. Unlike most Melbourne churches of the period, which are either [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] or [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]], Collins St Baptist is in the form of a classical temple, with four [[Corinthian columns]] facing the street. According to the church's website, this \"reflects the Baptist understanding of the church as a gathered community of believers rather than as a special building.\"\n\n==Building==\nIn conformity with the Baptist dislike of decoration in churches, the interior has plain plastered walls. It has arched moulded windows, a double aisle and side seats facing the [[pulpit]]. A central raised pulpit emphasises the stress in Baptist theology on the Word of God being read and preached as central features of the services of worship. Seating is arranged in a \"U\" shape around the central axis determined by the pulpit and the Communion table. There is no form of decoration other than some detail in the windows and carving on the pulpit and Communion furniture. No cross or symbol appears in the church.\n\nBaptist tradition also disapproved of music in churches, but in 1854 a small organ was installed. In 1885 the a larger organ was installed. This was restored and expanded in 1974.\n\nJim Barr was appointed a minister of Collins Street Baptist Church in 1991, when he established the Urban Mission Unit (now known as Urban Seed), recruited the first group of mission interns and implemented the SEEDS training program. This time was followed by his appointment as the Pastor at Collins Street Baptist Church from 1994 to 2000. During this time Jim was responsible for the pastoral and liturgical leadership of the Church community as well as taking a keen interest in the world around the Collins Street church.\n\n==People==\n[[Tim Costello]], a lawyer, republican activist and former [[St Kilda, Victoria|Mayor of St Kilda]] as well as a Baptist minister, was appointed the minister of the Collins Street Baptist Church and director of the Urban Mission Unit in 1995, the year before his brother, [[Peter Costello]], became the federal treasurer. Tim Costello's outspoken comments on many social and political issues brought new attention to the church. Under his leadership, the Urban Mission Unit rose to prominence as a leading voice on urban, business, social and political issues including homelessness, drug addiction, [[problem gambling]] and poverty.  The Urban Mission Unit changed its name to Urban Seed in 2001.  Costello left the position in 2004 on being appointed chief executive officer of [[World Vision]] Australia. The senior minister is now the Revd Simon Holt.\n\nSeveral historically notable people have been members of the church. During the early 20th century numerous women active in the Victorian women's movement were members, including [[Cecilia Downing]], [[Margaret McLean]] and [[Bessie Rees]].<ref>Smart, J. Downing, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A140031b.htm Cecilia (1858 - 1952)], Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 14, Melbourne University Press, 1996, pp 28-30.</ref><ref>Hyslop, A. McLean, Margaret (1845 - 1923), ''[http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A100322b.htm Australian Dictionary of Biography]'', Volume 10, Melbourne University Press, 1986, p. 331.</ref><ref>Smart, J, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/AS10409b.htm?hilite=Collins%3BStreet%3Bbaptist Rees, Elizabeth Laurie (Bessie) (1865 - 1939)], Australian Dictionary of Biography, Supplementary Volume, Melbourne University Press, 2005, pp 335-336.</ref> The politicians [[Denis Lovegrove]] and [[Robert Reid (Australian politician)|Robert Reid]] were members as were the prominent Melbourne Syme family, including the owner of ''The Age'', [[David Syme]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.csbc.org.au/ Collins Street Baptist Church]\n*[http://www.urbanseed.org/ Urban Seed]\n{{coord|-37.8148|144.9677|type:landmark_region:AU|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Baptist churches in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1862]]\n[[Category:19th-century Baptist churches]]\n[[Category:Heritage-listed buildings in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:1845 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Collins Street, Melbourne]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Robert Reid (Australian politician)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collins_Street_Baptist_Church"}
{"title_page": "If I Am President (2018 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = If I Am President\n| image          = File:If I Am President Movie 2018.jpg|thumb\n| director       = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| producer       = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| writer         = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Ayoola Ayolola]]|[[Joke Silva]]|[[Bimbo Manuel]]|Rekiya Atta|[[Uzee Usman]]|[[Rahama Sadau]]|[[Ivie Okujaye]]}}\n| cinematography = Ifeanyi Iloduba (BOKA)\n| editing        = Olamide Aremu (DOT COM)\n| studio         = High Definition Film Studio\n| promotions     = Virtues & Nobletouch Nigeria [[vntmedia]]\n| distributor    = Genesis Cinemas \n| released       = {{Film date|2018|11|09}}\n| runtime        = 120mins\n| country        = Nigeria\n| language       = English, Igbo, Hausa & Yoruba\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| website          ={{url|http://www.ifiampresidentmovie.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''''If I Am President''''' is a 2018 Nigerian political thriller film written, produced and directed by Bright Wonder Obasi, starring [[Ayoola Ayolola]], [[Joke Silva]], [[Bimbo Manuel]], [[Rahama Sadau]], [[Ivie Okujaye]], Rekiya Atta, [[Uzee Usman]]. It won award for Best Screenplay at the 2019 Motion Pictures International Film Festival (MOPIFF)<ref>https://drive.google.com/file/d/1QwZ8PQaYISu_0n0_zLy4y1KXHLvsCwAw/view</ref>.\n\n==Plot==\nSet in the present-day political terrain and discourses in Nigeria, \u201cIf I Am President\u201d tells the story of 37-year old ZinachiOhams, the presidential candidate of the Nigerian Rebirth Party, a new party made up of young idealists and recently metamorphosed from a Civil Society Organization. The group make a push into the murky and rough political terrain, armed with little more than their ideals, and wade through challenges of nasty politically engineered attacks, to emerge as the party and candidate to beat in the oncoming elections.\n\n[[File:IIAP movie poster.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ayoola Ayolola]] as Zina\n*[[Joke Silva]] as \n*Rekiya Atta as\n*[[Bimbo Manuel]] as Maurice\n*[[Rahama Sadau]]\n*[[Ivie Okujaye]] as\n*[[Bryan Okwara]] as\n*[[Uzee Usman]] as \n*Sydney Diala as\n*Ayo Emmanuel as\n*Norman Doo Moor as \n*[[Chimdiya Nwigwe]] as \n*[[Adaora Onyechere]] as Anchor\n*[[Rachel Bakam]] TV Presenter\n*Victor Decka\n*Osas Iyamu\t\t\t\n\n==Tagline==\nToday is the tomorrow we prayed for yesterday!\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Nigerian films of 2013]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{official website|http://http://www.ifiampresidentmovie.com/}}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2018 drama films]]\n[[Category:Nigerian films]]\n[[Category:Films by Nigerian directors]]\n[[Category:Nigerian drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = If I Am President\n| image          = File:If I Am President Movie 2018.jpg|thumb\n| director       = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| producer       = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| writer         = Bright Wonder Obasi\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Ayoola Ayolola]]|[[Joke Silva]]|[[Bimbo Manuel]]|Rekiya Atta|[[Uzee Usman]]|[[Rahama Sadau]]|[[Ivie Okujaye]]}}\n| cinematography = Ifeanyi Iloduba (BOKA)\n| editing        = Olamide Aremu (DOT COM)\n| studio         = High Definition Film Studio\n| promotions     = Virtues & Nobletouch Nigeria [[vntmedia]]\n| distributor    = Genesis Cinemas \n| released       = {{Film date|2018|11|09}}\n| runtime        = 120mins\n| country        = Nigeria\n| language       = English, Igbo, Hausa & Yoruba\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n}}\n\n'''''If I Am President''''' is a 2018 Nigerian political thriller film written, produced and directed by Bright Wonder Obasi, starring [[Ayoola Ayolola]], [[Joke Silva]], [[Bimbo Manuel]], [[Rahama Sadau]], [[Ivie Okujaye]], Rekiya Atta, [[Uzee Usman]]. It won award for Best Screenplay at the 2019 Motion Pictures International Film Festival (MOPIFF)<ref>https://drive.google.com/file/d/1QwZ8PQaYISu_0n0_zLy4y1KXHLvsCwAw/view</ref>.\n\n==Plot==\nSet in the present-day political terrain and discourses in Nigeria, \u201cIf I Am President\u201d tells the story of 37-year old ZinachiOhams, the presidential candidate of the Nigerian Rebirth Party, a new party made up of young idealists and recently metamorphosed from a Civil Society Organization. The group make a push into the murky and rough political terrain, armed with little more than their ideals, and wade through challenges of nasty politically engineered attacks, to emerge as the party and candidate to beat in the oncoming elections.\n\n[[File:IIAP movie poster.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ayoola Ayolola]] as Zina\n*[[Joke Silva]] as \n*Rekiya Atta as\n*[[Bimbo Manuel]] as Maurice\n*[[Rahama Sadau]]\n*[[Ivie Okujaye]] as\n*[[Bryan Okwara]] as\n*[[Uzee Usman]] as \n*Sydney Diala as\n*Ayo Emmanuel as\n*Norman Doo Moor as \n*[[Chimdiya Nwigwe]] as \n*[[Adaora Onyechere]] as Anchor\n*[[Rachel Bakam]] TV Presenter\n*Victor Decka\n*Osas Iyamu\t\t\t\n\n==Tagline==\nToday is the tomorrow we prayed for yesterday!\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Nigerian films of 2013]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{official website|http://http://www.ifiampresidentmovie.com/}}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2018 drama films]]\n[[Category:Nigerian films]]\n[[Category:Films by Nigerian directors]]\n[[Category:Nigerian drama films]]\n", "name_user": "Nnadi Duke", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/If_I_Am_President_(2018_film)"}
{"title_page": "MD", "text_new": "{{wiktionary|Md|.md}}\n'''MD''', '''Md''', '''mD''' or '''md''' may refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Places==\n* India\n*(ISO country code MD)\n* Bihar (state in India MD)\n* Muzaffarpur ( In city bihar india)\n*\n* Muzaffarpur ( Makdumpur Kodariya)\n\n==People==\n* [[Major Douglas]] (1879\u20131952), British Engineer and pioneer of the Social Credit economic reform movement\n* [[Muhammad (name)]] or Mohammed (Md)\n\n==Arts, entertainment, and media==\n===Music===\n* ''{{lang|fr|[[Main droite]]}}'' or ''{{lang|it|mano destra}}'' (MD or m.d.), used in piano scores to mark sequences of notes that are to be played with the right hand\n* [[MiniDisc]], an optical storage medium developed by Sony\n* [[Music director]]; the term \"MD\" is used particularly in musical theatre\n\n===Other arts, entertainment, and media===\n* [[MDs (TV series)|''MDs'' (TV series)]], a 2002 made-for-television medical drama\n* ''{{lang|it|[[Materiali e discussioni per l'analisi dei testi classici]]}}'', (\"Materials and discussions for the analysis of classical texts\"), an Italian classics journal\n* [[Mega Drive]], a game console produced by Sega\n\n==Brands and enterprises==\n* [[Air Madagascar]] (IATA airline code MD)\n* [[McDonnell Douglas]] (aircraft model prefix MD), a former aerospace manufacturer that later merged with Boeing\n\n==Science and technology==\n===Biology and medicine===\n* [[Doctor of Medicine]] (MD), from the Latin ''{{lang|la|Medicinae Doctor}}''\n* [[Medial dorsal nucleus]], a large nucleus in the thalamus\n* [[Muscular dystrophy]], a genetic and hereditary muscle disease\n* [[MD (Ayurveda)]], a degree in the Indian medical system of Ayurveda\n\n===Computing===\n* [[.md]], Internet top-level domain for Moldova\n* [[Markdown]] (file extension .md), a format\n* [[mdadm]] (multiple device), a device driver used to support RAID in the Linux kernel\n* [[Message-digest algorithm]], a cryptographic hashing function\n* [[Microdrive]], a type of m