\n===Team===\n*Australia is the most successful Test team in cricketing history. It has won more than 350 Test matches at a rate of almost 47%. The next best performance is by South Africa at 37%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/TESTS/RESULTS/TEST_RECORD_BY_COUNTRY.html |title=CricInfo Test Results by Country page |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=22 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070129061219/http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/TESTS/RESULTS/TEST_RECORD_BY_COUNTRY.html |archivedate=29 January 2007  }}</ref>\n*Australia have been involved in the only two [[Tied Test]]s played. The first occurred in December 1960, against the West Indies in Brisbane.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1960S/1960-61/WI_IN_AUS/WI_AUS_T1_09-14DEC1960.html |title=1st Test: Australia v West Indies at Brisbane, Dec 9\u201314, 1960 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040514020643/http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1960S/1960-61/WI_IN_AUS/WI_AUS_T1_09-14DEC1960.html |archive-date=14 May 2004 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second occurred in September 1986, against India in [[Madras]] ([[Chennai]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1980S/1986-87/AUS_IN_IND/AUS_IND_T1_18-22SEP1986.html |title=1st Test: India v Australia at Chennai, Sep 18\u201322, 1986 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119100029/http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1980S/1986-87/AUS_IN_IND/AUS_IND_T1_18-22SEP1986.html |archive-date=19 November 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Australia's largest  victory in a Test match came on 24 February 2002. Australia defeated South Africa by an innings and 360 runs in Johannesburg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/63978.html |title=1st Test: South Africa v Australia at Johannesburg, Feb 22\u201324, 2002 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119101238/http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/63978.html |archive-date=19 November 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Australia holds the record for the most consecutive wins with 16. This has been achieved twice; from October 1999 to February 2001 and from December 2005 to January 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/105118.html |title=Records &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318073831/http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/105118.html |archive-date=18 March 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Australia shares the record for the most consecutive series victories winning 9 series from October 2005 to June 2008. This record is shared with England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283958.html |title=Records &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330085820/http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283958.html |archive-date=30 March 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Australia's highest total in a Test match innings was recorded in Kingston, Jamaica against the West Indies in June 1955. Australia posted 758/8 in their first innings, with five players scoring a century.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/62793.html |title=5th Test: West Indies v Australia at Kingston, Jun 11\u201317, 1955 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707142024/http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/62793.html |archive-date=7 July 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Australia's lowest total in a Test match innings was recorded in Birmingham against England in May 1902. Australia were bowled all out for 36.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/62465.html |title=1st Test: England v Australia at Birmingham, May 29\u201331, 1902 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119110741/http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/62465.html |archive-date=19 November 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Australia are the only team to have lost a Test match after enforcing the [[follow-on]], having been the losing side in all three such matches:<ref>{{cite web| url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/TESTS/RESULTS/VICTORY_AFTER_FOLLOWING_ON.html| title=Tests \u2013 Victory after Following-On| publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]]| accessdate=2 October 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040627122908/http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/TESTS/RESULTS/VICTORY_AFTER_FOLLOWING_ON.html| archivedate=27 June 2004| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n**The first Test in the [[English cricket team in Australia in 1894\u201395|1894\u201395 Ashes]].\n**The [[Ian Botham#1981 Ashes Tour: Botham's Ashes|third Test]] of the [[Australian cricket team in England in 1981|1981 Ashes]].\n**The [[Australian cricket team in India in 2000\u201301#Second Test|second Test]] in the [[Australian cricket team in India in 2000\u201301|2000\u201301 Border-Gavaskar Trophy series]] against India.\n*Against India in March 2013, Australia became the first team in Test history to declare in their first innings and then lose by an innings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/21666135 |title=BBC Sport \u2013 India v Australia: Collapse helps hosts take 2\u20130 lead |publisher=BBC |date=5 March 2013 |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423121449/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/21666135 |archive-date=23 April 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*In the [[2013\u201314 Ashes series]], Australia took all 100 wickets on offer in the 5\u20130 sweep over England.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZEJFlAepE5Y |title=Aussies raise the bat, with the ball |work=Youtube |accessdate=7 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516205059/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZEJFlAepE5Y |archive-date=16 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Appearances===\n*[[Ricky Ponting]] and [[Steve Waugh]] have played in the most Test matches for Australia, both playing in 168 matches.\n\n===Batting===\n*[[Charles Bannerman]] faced the first ball in Test cricket, scored the first runs in Test cricket and also scored the first Test century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/17242338/charles-bannerman-australia-premier-batsman|title=What do we know about the first Test cricketer?|author=Gideon Haigh|date=7 August 2016|work=www.espncricinfo.com|access-date=27 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127143745/http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/17242338/charles-bannerman-australia-premier-batsman|archive-date=27 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Charles Bannerman also scored 67.34% of the Australian first innings total in match 1. This record remains to this day as the highest percentage of a completed innings total that has been scored by a single batsman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.howstat.com.au/cricket/Statistics/Batting/Batting50Percent.asp |title=Batsmen Scoring more than 50% of Innings Total (where side dismissed) |publisher=Howstat! |accessdate=30 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410130622/http://www.howstat.com.au/cricket/statistics/Batting/Batting50Percent.asp |archive-date=10 April 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Ricky Ponting has scored the most runs for Australia in Test cricket with 13,378 runs. [[Allan Border]] is second with 11,174 runs in 265 innings while Steve Waugh has 10,927 in 260 innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?class=1;id=2;type=team |title=Cricket Records &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>\n*Allan Border was the first Australian batsman to pass 10,000 and the first ever batsman to pass 11,000 Test runs.\n*Ricky Ponting was the first Australian batsman to pass 12,000 and 13,000 Test runs.\n*[[Matthew Hayden]] holds the record for the most runs in a single innings by an Australian with 380 in the first Test against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] in Perth in October 2003.\n*[[Donald Bradman]] holds the record for the highest average by an Australian (or any other) cricketer of 99.94 runs per dismissal. Bradman played 52 Tests, scoring 29 centuries and a further 13 fifties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/records/batting/highest_career_batting_average.html?class=1;id=2;type=team |title=Cricket Records &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>\n*Ricky Ponting holds the record for the most centuries by an Australian cricketer with 41. Former Australian captain Steve Waugh is in second position with 32 centuries from 260 innings.<ref name=\"content-aus.cricinfo.com\">{{cite web|url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/records/batting/most_fifties_career.html?class=1;id=2;type=team |title=Cricket Records &#124; Most fifties (and over) &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>\n*Allan Border holds the record for the most fifties by an Australian cricketer with 63 in 265 innings.<ref name=\"content-aus.cricinfo.com\"/>\n*[[Adam Gilchrist]] holds the record for the fastest century by an Australian.\n*[[Glenn McGrath]] holds the record for the most [[Duck (cricket)|ducks]] by an Australian cricketer with 35 in 138 innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/records/batting/most_ducks_career.html?class=1;id=2;type=team |title=Cricket Records &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Bowling===\n*[[Billy Midwinter]] picked up the first five-wicket haul in a Test innings in match 1.<ref name=\"Cricinfo Match Scorecard\">{{cite web |url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/62396.html |title=1st Test: Australia v England at Melbourne, Mar 15\u201319, 1877 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130119235459/http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/62396.html |archive-date=19 January 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Fred Spofforth]] performed Test cricket's first [[Hat-trick (cricket)|hat-trick]] by dismissing Vernon Royle, Francis McKinnon and Tom Emmett in successive balls.<ref name=test3>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/136977.html |title=Records &#124; Hat-tricks &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321205721/http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/136977.html |archive-date=21 March 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Fred Spofforth also took the first 10-wicket match haul in Test cricket.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n*[[Shane Warne]] holds the record for the most wickets by an Australian cricketer with 708 wickets in 145 Test matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?class=1;id=2;type=team |title=Cricket Records &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Arthur Mailey]] holds the record for the best bowling figures in an innings by an Australian cricketer with 9/121 against England in February 1921.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/62524.html |title=4th Test: Australia v England at Melbourne, Feb 11\u201316, 1921 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014142059/http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/62524.html |archive-date=14 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Bob Massie]] holds the record for the best bowling figures in a match by an Australian cricketer with 16/137 against England in June 1972. That was also his first Test match for Australia.<ref name=\"CricInfo page\">{{cite web|url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/records/bowling/best_career_bowling_average.html?class=1;id=2;type=team |title=Cricket Records &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>\n*[[John Ferris (cricketer)|J. J. Ferris]] holds the record for the best bowling average by an Australian bowler, taking 61 wickets at 12.70 in his career.<ref name=\"CricInfo page\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-www.cricinfo.com/australia/content/player/5225.html |title=J.J. Ferris &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-www.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070323032340/http://content-www.cricinfo.com/australia/content/player/5225.html |archive-date=23 March 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Clarrie Grimmett]] holds the record for the most wickets in a Test series with 44 against South Africa in 1935\u201336.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_series.html?class=1;id=2;type=team |title=Cricket Records &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Fielding and wicketkeeping===\n*[[Ricky Ponting]] holds the record for the most catches in a career by an Australian fielder with 196 in 168 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/records/fielding/most_catches_career.html?class=1;id=2;type=team |title=Cricket Records &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Jack Blackham]] performed the first stumping in Test cricket in match 1.<ref name=\"Cricinfo Match Scorecard\"/>\n*[[Adam Gilchrist]] holds the record for the most dismissals in a career by an Australian wicketkeeper with 416 in 96 matches.\n\n==One-Day International records==\n{{Main|List of Australia One Day International cricket records}}\n{{see also|List of 400+ innings scores in ODIs}}\n\n===Team===\n*Australia's highest total in a One-Day International innings is 434/4, scored off 50 overs against South Africa in Johannesburg on 12 March 2006. This was a world record score before the South Africans later surpassed it in the same match.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/238200.html |title=5th ODI: South Africa v Australia at Johannesburg, Mar 12, 2006, &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210085509/http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/match/238200.html |archive-date=10 February 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Australia's lowest total in a One-Day International innings is 70. This score has occurred twice; once against England in 1977 and once against New Zealand in 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/engine/records/team/lowest_innings_totals.html?class=2;id=2;type=team |title=Cricket Records &#124; One-Day Internationals &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>\n*Australia's largest victory in One-Day International cricket is 275 runs. This occurred against [[Afghanistan national cricket team|Afghanistan]] at the [[2015 Cricket World Cup|2015 World Cup]] in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/content/story/843137.html |title=31st Match: Australia v Namibia at Potchefstroom, Feb 27, 2003 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=22 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306022532/http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/content/story/843137.html |archive-date=6 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Australia are the only team in the history of the [[Cricket World Cup|World Cup]] to win 3 consecutive tournaments; [[1999 Cricket World Cup|1999]], [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003]] and [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007]].\n*Australia went undefeated at the World Cup for a record 34 consecutive matches. After being defeated by Pakistan in [[1999 Cricket World Cup|1999]], Australia would remain unbeaten until they were again defeated by Pakistan in [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011]].\n*Australia have won the most World Cups \u2013 5.\n\n===Appearances===\n*Ricky Ponting has played in the most One-Day International matches for Australia, playing 395 matches.\n\n===Batting===\n*[[Ricky Ponting]] has the most One-Day International runs by an Australian batsman with 13,291.\n*Ricky Ponting has the most One-Day International centuries by an Australian batsman with 30.\n*Ricky Ponting has the most One-Day International fifties by an Australian batsman with 82.\n*Ricky Ponting is the first Australian batsman to pass 10,000 One-Day International runs.\n*[[Shane Watson]] has the highest individual [[Not out (cricket)|not out]] score in an innings by an Australian batsman with 185[[Not out (cricket)|*]].\n*Shane Watson has hit the most [[Six (cricket)|sixes]] in a single innings by an Australian player with 15.\n*[[Phillip Hughes]] was the only Australian player to score a century on debut in One-Day International cricket.\n\n===Bowling===\n*Glenn McGrath has the most One-Day International wickets by an Australian bowler with 381.\n*Glenn McGrath has the best bowling figures by an Australian bowler with 7/15.\n*Brett Lee has the most five-wicket hauls by an Australian bowler with 9.\n\n===Fielding and wicketkeeping===\n*Ricky Ponting has the most catches taken by an Australian fielder with 154.\n*Adam Gilchrist has the most dismissals by an Australian wicketkeeper with 470.\n*Adam Gilchrist has the most catches taken by an Australian wicketkeeper with 416.\n*Adam Gilchrist has the most stumpings made by an Australian wicketkeeper with 54.\n\n==Tournament history==\n''A red box around the year indicates tournaments played within Australia''\n\n===ICC World Cup===\n{{main|Australia at the Cricket World Cup}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=9|[[Cricket World Cup|World Cup record]]\n|-\n! width=150 |Year\n! width=150 |Round\n! width=50 |Position\n! width=50 |GP\n! width=50 |W\n! width=50 |L\n! width=50 |T\n! width=50 |NR\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[1975 Cricket World Cup|1975]]|| Runners-up||2/8||5||3||2||0||0\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[1979 Cricket World Cup|1979]]||rowspan=2|Group stage||rowspan=2|6/8||3||1||2||0||0\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[1983 Cricket World Cup|1983]]||6||2||4||0||0\n|- style=\"background:gold;\"\n|{{flagicon|IND}} {{flagicon|PAK}} [[1987 Cricket World Cup|1987]]||'''Champions'''||1/8||8||7||1||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{flagicon|AUS}} {{flagicon|NZL}} [[1992 Cricket World Cup|1992]]||Round 1||5/9||8||4||4||0||0\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n|{{flagicon|IND}} {{flagicon|PAK}} {{flagicon|SRI}} [[1996 Cricket World Cup|1996]]||Runners-up||2/12||7||5||2||0||0\n|- style=\"background:gold;\"\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[1999 Cricket World Cup|1999]]||rowspan=3|'''Champions'''||1/12||10||7||2||1||0\n|- style=\"background:gold;\"\n|{{flagicon|RSA}} [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003]]||1/14||11||11||0||0||0\n|- style=\"background:gold;\"\n|{{flagicon|WIN}} [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007]]||1/16||11||11||0||0||0\n|- style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"\n|{{flagicon|IND}} {{flagicon|SRI}} {{flagicon|BGD}} [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011]]||Quarter-finals||6/14||7||4||2||0||1\n|- style=\"background:gold;\"\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{flagicon|AUS}} {{flagicon|NZL}} [[2015 Cricket World 